            "abstractNote": "Diet and habitat selection of several species of insectivorous bats were studied in the Dead Sea area, Israel. Significant differences in diet composition were found among the species studied. Long-eared bats (Plecorus QllstriaClls and Nycreris !hchaica) tended to feed on Lepidoptera, and N. thebaica also on Diptcra; AseLlia tridens and Rhin%plllis ciivoSllS on Coleoptera and Hymenoptera; RhinolophllS hipposideros on Lepidoptera and Diptera; Eplesiclls bottae on Hymenopter<l and Lepidoptera; Pipislrelllls bodenheimeri and Pipistrellus kuhlii on Diptera and Lepidoptera; and PipislreJlus rueppellii on Diptera. Dietary niche breadlh (B%v) was widest for P bodenheimeri and narrowest for P. auslriacus. There were significant species-related dilTerences in habitat utilization. Tadarida tel/iotis and Rhinopoma hardwickei foraged almost exclusively in open areas; 'over water' habitat was preferred by P. rlieppeLLii and utilized extensively also by P. bodenheimeri; 'ne<lr street lights' <lnd 'edges of vegetation and cl iffs' by P. kuhlii; 'edges of vegetation and cliITs' by P. bodenheimeri and E. bouae; and 'cluttered environment' by A. tridens, R. hipposideros, and R. c1ivosus. Community structure of these bats is discussed.",
