            "title": "SEASONAL FOOD RESOURCES AND PREY SELECTION OF THE SOUTHEASTERN BROWN BAT (MYOTIS AUSTRORIPARIUS) IN FLORIDA",
            "creators": [],
            "abstractNote": "Prey availability and changes in food selection by M. austroriparius were exam ined on 3 nights, 1 during the period of lactation in early summer and 2 during the intermittan cold weather in early spring. Analysis was based on 669 whole insects and 93 fecal pellets. \"Warm temperate zone weather strongly influences insect availability and hence the phenology of this i sectivorous bat. On the colder spring night, only Diptera were active, and the bats selected th largest—mosquitoes and crane flies. On the warmer spring and summer nights, flying insect were more diverse and abundant, and the bats selected several kinds with a preference order o Coleoptera, Lepidoptera, and culicid Diptera. Though feeding as generalists on several pre taxa, the bats appeared to select prey on the basis of size within taxonomic groups. The lon period of ample food supply for warm temperate M. austroriparius contrasts with the short gro ing season for cool temperate Myotis lucifugus and with year-round food availability for tropica emballonurids, with distinct implications for timing and duration of bat reproduction in the zones. Seasonal differences in food supply may also influence the size of summer and winter col onies.",
